{{italic title}}{{Expand Japanese|date=January 2023}}

{{Nihongo|2=新国史|3='''''Shinkokushi'''''|4={{lit|New National History}}}} is an unfinished [[Japan|Japanese]] official historical work compiled, in part, by the early [[Heian period]] scholar {{illm|Ōe no Asatsuna|ja|大江朝綱}}, grandson of [[Ōe no Otondo]], who had been one of the compilers of the ''[[Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku]]''.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book |last=Sakamoto |first=Taro |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L7KSWxhOPrMC |title=The Six National Histories of Japan |date=2011-11-01 |publisher=UBC Press |isbn=978-0-7748-4296-9 |pages=187–191 |language=en}}</ref> After Asatsuna's death in 957, his cousin Ōe no Koretoki became the head compiler. It was supposed to succeed the ''[[Rikkokushi|Six National Histories]]''.<ref>Taniguchi Akira. [https://kotobank.jp/word/%E6%96%B0%E5%9B%BD%E5%8F%B2-1176406 ''Nihon Dai Hyakka Zensho (Nipponica)'']. [[Shōgakukan]]</ref>

The ''Shinkokushi'' is recorded in the ''{{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Honchō Shojoku Mokuroku|ja|本朝書籍目録|WD=}}'' as having forty volumes and covering the reigns of [[Emperor Uda]] (887-897) to [[Emperor Daigo]] (897-930). However a later work, the ''{{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Shūgaisho (encyclopedia)|lt=Shūgaisho|ja|拾芥抄}}'', states that the ''Shinkokushi'' was fifty volumes and included the reign of [[Emperor Suzaku]] (930-946) as well as Uda and Daigo.<ref name=":0" /> Because of the differences in size, lack of a formal title, and that no record of a presentation of the work survives, it is believed that the ''Shinkokushi'' was an unfinished manuscript.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite book |last=Brownlee |first=John S. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uF09DgAAQBAJ |title=Political Thought in Japanese Historical Writing: From Kojiki (712) to Tokushi Yoron (1712) |date=2006-01-01 |publisher=Wilfrid Laurier Univ. Press |isbn=978-0-88920-874-2 |pages=40 |language=en}}</ref> As a manuscript, the entirety of the ''Shinkokushi'' does not survive but instead portions of it have been passed down in other works.
